    <h1>Recipe: AtlasArc in your build</h1>
    <p>AtlasArc is an analysis tool. It helps you <em>see</em> architectural drift inside IntelliJ IDEA and record deliberate exceptions in your source. It does not gate your build. Gating is <a href="https://www.archunit.org/">ArchUnit</a>'s job, and AtlasArc makes a good friend: AtlasArc's acceptance annotations are ordinary, bytecode-visible Java annotations, so a handful of lines of ArchUnit turn the decisions you made while exploring into a rule your pipeline enforces.</p>
    <p>The result: a new, un-sanctioned package cycle fails CI, while the cycles you deliberately sanctioned in the IDE are ignored automatically, with no AtlasArc runtime anywhere in your build.</p>

    <h2>How it fits together</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>AtlasArc (IDE)</strong>: you find a cycle, decide it is intentional, and record it at the declaration with <code>@AllowIncomingPackageCycle</code> or <code>@AllowOutgoingPackageCycle</code>. The reason and ticket travel into code review.</li>
      <li><strong>ArchUnit (CI)</strong>: your test suite runs a standard cycle rule that reads those same annotations from compiled bytecode and excludes the sanctioned edges. Everything else still fails the build.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>One decision, recorded once, honoured in both places.</p>

    <h2>1. Add the dependencies</h2>
    <p>The annotations artifact is published to Maven Central. You need it only at compile time; ArchUnit lives in your test scope.</p>
    <pre><code>// build.gradle.kts
dependencies {
    // AtlasArc acceptance annotations: compile-time only, no runtime footprint.
    compileOnly("io.atlasarc:atlasarc-annotations:1.0.0") // see Maven Central for the current version

    // ArchUnit: your enforcement engine (JUnit 5 integration shown).
    testImplementation("com.tngtech.archunit:archunit-junit5:1.4.2")
}</code></pre>
    <p>Maven is equivalent: a <code>provided</code>-scope dependency on <code>io.atlasarc:atlasarc-annotations</code> and a <code>test</code>-scope dependency on <code>com.tngtech.archunit:archunit-junit5</code>.</p>

    <h2>2. Sanction cycles where they belong</h2>
    <p>This is the step you already do in AtlasArc. The IDE can write these markers for you. The annotation goes on the declaration that anchors the intentional edge: <code>@AllowOutgoingPackageCycle</code> on the <em>origin</em> side (the class that depends out), or <code>@AllowIncomingPackageCycle</code> on the <em>target</em> side (the class being depended on).</p>
    <pre><code>// billing/Invoice.java: the back-reference into orders is deliberate.
@AllowOutgoingPackageCycle(reason = "an invoice resolves its order via the order service")
public class Invoice { /* ... */ }</code></pre>

    <h2>3. Add the ArchUnit rule</h2>
    <p>Start from ArchUnit's standard cycle check, then exclude the edges your annotations sanction: outgoing on the origin, incoming on the target.</p>
    <pre><code>import com.tngtech.archunit.base.DescribedPredicate;
import com.tngtech.archunit.core.domain.JavaClass;
import com.tngtech.archunit.junit.AnalyzeClasses;
import com.tngtech.archunit.junit.ArchTest;
import com.tngtech.archunit.lang.ArchRule;
import io.atlasarc.annotations.AllowIncomingPackageCycle;
import io.atlasarc.annotations.AllowOutgoingPackageCycle;

import static com.tngtech.archunit.base.DescribedPredicate.alwaysTrue;
import static com.tngtech.archunit.library.dependencies.SlicesRuleDefinition.slices;

@AnalyzeClasses(packages = "com.myapp")
class ArchitectureTest {

    static final DescribedPredicate&lt;JavaClass&gt; ORIGIN_SANCTIONS_OUTGOING =
        DescribedPredicate.describe("origin annotated @AllowOutgoingPackageCycle",
            c -&gt; c.isAnnotatedWith(AllowOutgoingPackageCycle.class));

    static final DescribedPredicate&lt;JavaClass&gt; TARGET_SANCTIONS_INCOMING =
        DescribedPredicate.describe("target annotated @AllowIncomingPackageCycle",
            c -&gt; c.isAnnotatedWith(AllowIncomingPackageCycle.class));

    @ArchTest
    static final ArchRule packagesFreeOfUnsanctionedCycles =
        slices().matching("com.myapp.(*)..")
            .should().beFreeOfCycles()
            .ignoreDependency(ORIGIN_SANCTIONS_OUTGOING, alwaysTrue())
            .ignoreDependency(alwaysTrue(), TARGET_SANCTIONS_INCOMING);
}</code></pre>
    <p>Run it the way you run any test: <code>./gradlew test</code>, <code>mvn test</code>, or your CI step. An un-sanctioned cycle fails the build with ArchUnit's usual report; a sanctioned one is silently excluded.</p>

    <h2>What this covers, and what it doesn't</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Class- and package-level acceptance: fully honoured.</strong> ArchUnit's <code>ignoreDependency</code> predicates operate on the type, so a marker on a class (or on a <code>package-info.java</code>) is read exactly as the IDE reads it.</li>
      <li><strong>Member-level acceptance: out of scope.</strong> AtlasArc's IDE overlay can honour an annotation on a single method or field; the ArchUnit predicate above sees only the class. For CI parity, keep build-enforced exceptions at class or package level. The IDE will agree with the rule, and vice versa.</li>
      <li><strong>The <code>packages()</code> counterparty filter is not applied, and this fails open.</strong> The predicate above treats any annotated class as a blanket sanction. The IDE, by contrast, honours <code>@AllowOutgoingPackageCycle(packages = {"com.foo"})</code> as narrowing acceptance to just the <code>com.foo</code> counterparty. <code>ignoreDependency</code> evaluates the origin and target predicates independently, so it cannot correlate one side's annotation parameter with the other side's package. That means the CI rule will exclude <em>more</em> than the IDE does. If you rely on <code>packages()</code> narrowing, do not treat those edges as CI-enforced; use a blanket (no-<code>packages()</code>) annotation for anything the build must guard.</li>
      <li><strong>Intentional vs. debt.</strong> The recipe treats every sanctioned cycle the same. If you want CI to pass on <code>kind = INTENTIONAL</code> but only <em>warn</em> on <code>kind = DEBT</code>, read the annotation parameter in your predicate and split it into two rules.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Prefer a baseline over per-edge annotations? ArchUnit's <code>FreezingArchRule</code> grandfathers existing cycles into a stored snapshot and fails only on new ones. That is a complementary model when you are retrofitting a large codebase and not ready to annotate every exception yet.</p>

    <h2>A note on reliability</h2>
    <p>The rule above is not illustrative pseudo-code. It is exercised by an automated test in AtlasArc's own build, against fixtures that contain real package cycles sanctioned in both directions. The test brackets the behaviour: a plain cycle rule is asserted to fail, the annotation-aware rule is asserted to pass when every edge is sanctioned, and, crucially, the same rule is asserted to <em>still fail</em> on an un-sanctioned cycle. That proves the exclusion is targeted rather than fail-open. The recipe is kept honest as AtlasArc and ArchUnit evolve.</p>

    <h2>Related</h2>
